Implementing Prefers Reduced Motion

02

If you do have large amounts of movement that cover a lot of visual real estate, it is strongly recommended that you offer an option to turn off, or reduce, motion.

Having your site implement support for prefers-reduced-motion is a great way to give control to the user for their preference at the operating system (OS) level.

The prefers-reduced-motion media feature is used to detect if the user has requested that the system minimize the amount of motion it uses.

This change takes place not only in the browser, but at the OS level as well.

For example, on a Mac, you can stop or reduce the movement of some elements on the screen—when you open apps, switch between desktops, or open and close Notification Center.

To enable this, you can follow these steps:

  1. On your Mac, choose Apple menu > System Preferences, click Accessibility, then click Display.
  2. Select Reduce motion.

Reduced motion is also supported on Windows and a variety of mobile platforms.

On the web development side, we can test for prefers-reduced-motion in the same way that we would use any other media query in CSS or JavaScript to find out if reduced motion has been requested.

@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  .animation {
    animation: none;
    transition: none;
  }
}
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  .animation {
    animation: none;
    transition: none;
  }
}

Or using the JavaScript matchMedia API:

var motionQuery = matchMedia('(prefers-reduced-motion)');
function handleReduceMotionChanged() {
    if (motionQuery.matches) {
        /* adjust 'transition' or 'animation' properties */
    } else {
        /* standard motion */
    }
}
motionQuery.addEventListener('change', handleReduceMotionChanged);
handleReduceMotionChanged(); // trigger once on load
var motionQuery = matchMedia('(prefers-reduced-motion)');
function handleReduceMotionChanged() {
    if (motionQuery.matches) {
        /* adjust 'transition' or 'animation' properties */
    } else {
        /* standard motion */
    }
}
motionQuery.addEventListener('change', handleReduceMotionChanged);
handleReduceMotionChanged(); // trigger once on load

Note: you can also match on prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference to provide more of an opt-in approach to animation.

The prefers-reduced-motion media feature now has strong browser support, so there is no excuse not to use it. You can always provide an additional custom toggle or user setting in your application if needed on other platforms.
